  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Environmentally Sound Management and Final Disposal of PCBs at the Russian Railroad network and other PCB owners (Phase I)</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The project will assist the country to establish ESM system for PCBs, focusing on one of the companies with most PCBs in the country taking the lead role in providing space and resources to operate the proposed PCB facilities. The operation of the management and disposal facilities to be established will offer PCB disposal and treatment services to other PCB users in Russia.

Although with a number of rules and regulations covering some aspects of PCBs as a waste stream, Russia does not have overwhelming specific PCB regulations that define their use, management, disposal and use of them in electrical equipment. Institutional capacity building, development of regulatory and policy framework will need to be strengthened. The GEF project is envisaged to assist in the establishment of an Environmentally Sound Management System managing PCBs in use and as waste, the development and implementation of rules and guidelines for the management of PCBs, capacity building for government officials, workers and PCB owners, determination of contaminated equipment and wastes, the establishment of proven, commercially available transportation and PCB treatment
technologies for safe disposal of PCBs and the treatment of 3,800 metric tons of PCB-containing equipment and waste thereby reducing the potential release of PCBs into the environment.

Based on preliminary assessment through this project, technologies for the dechlorination of PCB contaminated oil and decontamination of metallic and porous materials from PCB containing transformers will be established in the selected site and use to treat the 3,800 tons of PCB contaminated
equipment and wastes during the life of the project.

The treatment technologies will be installed in an industrial site at Yaroslavl, owned and operated by the Railroad Company (RZD), one of the project&apos;s partners. The mobile technology will be set up to serve the needs of the other potential partners.

The selection of technologies will be done based on their BAT characteristics and priority will be given to those, which could be locally produced, thus the process of a technology transfer will be an integral part
of the project and the local businesses will have tested projects for reproduction in other regions and for large owners of contaminated equipment.

The proposed sampling and analysis of 50,000 transformers included in this project will help the country to have a much better understanding of the spread of PCB contamination in electrical transformers. The development of a database and GIS system to register and manage PCB-containing equipment in this project will help government environmental agencies to better control and PCB users to better manage their PCB-containing equipment, therefore reducing the potential for unlawful disposal of these materials and to facilitate the reporting of the country&#x2019;s progress in the elimination of PCBs.

As part of this project significant efforts will spend on training of government officials, PCB owners, and workers dealing with PCBs on how to identify PCBs and to establish mechanisms to prevent leakage and cross contamination, safe handling and storage of the equipment. ESM of PCBs shall also be properly disseminated among relevant stakeholders including conduct of inventory, proper registration, labeling and storage of PCB wastes and PCB contaminated equipment. Technical and human resource capacity of at least 2 laboratories will also be enhanced. Based on the NIP, currently, no laboratory in the country is accredited to analyze PCBs.

The significant fraction of the 3,800 metric tons of PCB-containing equipment to be treated in this proposed project will be provided by the RZD Company; a removal and replacement plan of PCB containing transformers will be developed and implemented jointly with the management of this company.

Based on the successful implementation of such a plan, state-owned as well as private entities will be encouraged and supported to implement similar plans in their facilities. Thus, the successful implementation of this project will have a significant impact on the country&#x2019;s efforts to eliminate its PCBs and its ability to meet the obligations under the Stockholm Convention.

The GEF scenario will support the baseline project by providing a holistic environmentally sound management of PCBs in Russia. In the absence of GEF funding, the capacity for PCBs management as well as legal and institutional frameworks would improve slowly. Without assistance, replacement of existing equipment containing PCBs would continue at the current rate and without proper registration and assurance of its proper disposal. The installation of proper interim storage facilities to collect PCBs
and ensure its proper disposal would be slower at best creating a significant environmental risk if these wastes were not safe disposed.</narrative>
  </description>
